  "prompt": "Can i send my GRE scores to the four universities freely?",
  "response": "Yes, when you take the GRE, you are allowed to send your scores to up to **four** institutions for **free**. This is part of your registration fee.\n\nThis option is available **at the test center** on the day you take the test.  You'll be asked to select which institutions you want to send your scores to before you see your official scores.\n\nKeep in mind:\n\n*   **Choose wisely:** Once you send them, you can't change those four free selections.\n*   **After the test:** If you want to send scores to more than four institutions, or if you decide later to send scores to schools you didn't choose on test day, you'll have to pay a fee for each additional score report.\n*   **ScoreSelect:** ETS (the company that administers the GRE) offers a service called ScoreSelect.  This allows you to choose which scores you want to send to schools.  So if you take the GRE multiple times, you can send only the scores from the test date you are most happy with. You can use Score Select even for the free reports you choose on test day.\n*   **Check University Requirements:** Make absolutely sure you are sending your scores to the correct department and using the correct ETS institutional code for each university. These codes are very important and ensure your scores get to the right place.\n*   **Deadlines:** Ensure you send your scores with plenty of time for them to arrive by the university application deadlines. The ETS website provides estimated delivery times, but it's always best to allow extra time.\n*   **Timing:** You see unofficial scores for Verbal Reasoning and Quantitative Reasoning immediately after you complete the test. You **don't** see your Analytical Writing score. Because you see these unofficial scores, you can make a more informed decision about which four schools to send your scores to.\n    \n\nTherefore, take advantage of the four free score reports offered as part of your GRE registration fee. Research the ETS codes for the universities you are interested in beforehand. Good luck!\n",
